1.2 Via ‘use-package’ and ‘:vc’
===============================

Since version 30, Emacs has the ‘:vc’ keyword for ‘use-package’ built-in
which enables users to install packages using packages using
‘package-vc’, i.e.  via version control systems like Git.  You can use
it as follows to install Nael:

     (use-package nael
       :vc ( :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git"
             :lisp-dir "nael"))

     ;; Optional:

     (use-package nael-markdown
       :after markdown-mode
       :vc ( :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git"
             :lisp-dir "nael-markdown"))

     (use-package nael-lsp
       :after nael
       :vc ( :url "https://codeberg.org/mekeor/nael.git"
             :lisp-dir "nael-lsp"))

   Because each package has autoload-cookies on relevant expressions,
and because ‘use-package’ will load each package's ‘*-autoloads.el’ file
that is generated at installation, you don't need to specify
load-triggeres like ‘:mode’ or ‘:defer t’.

   (Unfortunately, Emacs' built-in ‘package-vc’ will byte-compile the
Elisp source files of all packages inside Nael's Git repository.  Please
ignore the resulting compilation warnings.)


